# AIGX — AI Genome Exchange

This repo stores its agent rules in `.aigx/` — a structured genome that describes every important file's purpose, forbidden imports, and worst gotchas. **You do not need to guess conventions; they are in the genome.**

---

## Before touching any file — look it up

Find the file in `.aigx/files.aigx`. Every file an agent is likely to edit has a `<file path="...">` entry:

```xml
<file path="src/features/auth/login.ts" domain="auth">
  <role>Handle login — validate credentials and issue a session</role>
  <forbid pri="CRIT">NEVER read from another tenant's session store</forbid>
  <gotcha>token expiry is checked at read-time, not issue-time</gotcha>
  <check>ARCH-no-deep-imports ENG-tenant-scope</check>
</file>
```

Read it, then:

| Field | What it means | How to act |
|---|---|---|
| `<role>` | What this file is for | Understand it before writing a line |
| `<forbid pri="CRIT">` | Hard constraint — a NEVER | Never violate it. Not "try not to" — never. |
| `<gotcha>` | The single worst pitfall here | Read it twice |
| `<check>` | Rule ids to verify before finishing | Look each up in its concern file |

---

## The genome structure

```
.aigx/
  protocol.aigx      ← full reading sequence
  product.aigx       ← product context + which older docs are stale (freshness clause)
  architecture.aigx  ← ARCH-* rules
  data.aigx          ← DATA-* rules   (if present)
  auth.aigx          ← AUTH-* rules   (if present)
  engineering.aigx   ← ENG-* hard-correctness invariants
  files.aigx         ← ★ per-file boundary index (the keystone — look files up here)
  agent.aigx         ← self-maintenance rules for agents
  [more].aigx        ← any other concern (testing, performance, security, …)
```

Check ids in `<check>` resolve to rules in concern files. `ARCH-no-deep-imports` → look in `architecture.aigx` for `<rule id="ARCH-no-deep-imports">`. Read that rule before writing code.

---

## Keeping the genome current — non-negotiable

The genome is only useful if it stays true to the codebase.

**When you rename or move a file** that has a `files.aigx` entry: update `path="..."` in the **same change-set**. A rename that doesn't update the genome is an incomplete change.

**When you create a new source file** agents will edit: add a `<file>` entry in `files.aigx`. Minimum: `<role>` + one `<check>` id. Never leave a new boundary file undocumented.

**Rule ids are permanent.** `ARCH-no-deep-imports`, `ENG-2`, etc. — never rename or delete them. If a rule's meaning changes, update the text in-place. The id stays forever.

**When your code change makes a rule incorrect:** update the rule text in the same change-set. The genome must describe reality, not history.

**After any task that moves, deletes, or adds files:** confirm every `<file path>` in `files.aigx` still exists and every `<check>` id still resolves to a real rule.

**Never add entries speculatively.** One entry per file agents actually edit. One rule per real constraint. Lean genomes outperformed rich ones in the benchmark.

